<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="20" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,756,1487,1798]" pageId="9" pageNumber="20">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,262,1488,1512]" pageId="9" pageNumber="20">Diagnosis</emphasis>
: This species is similar in size and wing markings to 
<taxonomicName authority="Hampson" authorityName="Hampson" box="[327,691,1519,1544]" class="Insecta" family="Crambidae" genus="Conotalis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigrisquamalis">
<emphasis box="[327,541,1519,1544]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="20">A. nigrisquamalis</emphasis>
(Hampson)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Bleszynski" authorityName="Bleszynski" box="[151,393,1551,1576]" class="Insecta" family="Crambidae" genus="Aurotalis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dionisa">
<emphasis box="[151,263,1551,1576]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="20">A. dionisa</emphasis>
Błeszyński
</taxonomicName>
, but the forewing ground colour is darker with narrow, orange, median and subterminal fasciae, and the hindwings are white suffused brown. In male genitalia, the phallus with a single blunt cornutus will separate this species from other members of the genus. In female genitalia, the ductus bursae funnelshaped and lightly sclerotized only near corpus bursae is diagnostic.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
